{"title_page": "Colsterworth", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2014}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n| country = England\n| coordinates = {{coord|52.80554|-0.61825|display=inline,title}}\n| official_name = Colsterworth\n| static_image_name = St John the Baptist, Colsterworth 8.jpg\n| static_image_caption = Parish church of St John the Baptist\n| population = 1,713\n| civil_parish = Colsterworth\n| shire_district = [[South Kesteven]]\n| shire_county = [[Lincolnshire]]\n| region = East Midlands\n| constituency_westminster = [[Grantham and Stamford (UK Parliament constituency)|Grantham and Stamford]]\n| post_town = GRANTHAM\n| postcode_district = NG33\n| postcode_area = NG\n| dial_code = \n| os_grid_reference = SK932240\n| london_distance_mi = 90<!-- straight line per MOS \u2013 constant and comparable with other place distances -->\n| london_direction = S\n}}\n'''Colsterworth''' is a village and [[civil parish]] in the [[South Kesteven]] district of [[Lincolnshire]], England. It lies less than half a mile (0.8&nbsp;km) west of the [[A1 road (Great Britain)|A1]], about {{convert|7|mi|km|0}} south of [[Grantham]], and {{convert|12|mi|km|0}} north-west of [[Stamford, Lincolnshire|Stamford]]. The village, with the hamlet of [[Woolsthorpe-by-Colsterworth]], had a population of 1,713 at the time of the 2011 Census in an area of {{convert|1465|ha}}.<ref>Office of National Statistics [http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=7&b=11122217&c=Colsterworth&d=16&e=61&g=6447427&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&p=1&r=1&s=1454584397276&enc=1&dsFamilyId=2491 Retrieved 4 February 2016.]</ref>\n\n==Civil parish==\nThe civil parish includes the village of Woolsthorpe-by-Colsterworth, {{convert|0.6|mi|0}} north-west of Colsterworth. The parish shares a [[grouped parish council]] with [[Gunby and Stainby]] and [[North Witham]], known as Colsterworth and District Parish Council.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Colsterworth and District Parishes |url=http://parishes.lincolnshire.gov.uk/ColsterworthandDistrict/|work=Lincolnshire Parish Councils; South Kesteven |publisher=Lincolnshire county council |accessdate=8 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Woolsthorpe-by-Colsterworth===\n{{main|Woolsthorpe-by-Colsterworth}}\nWoolsthorpe-by-Colsterworth is notable as the birthplace of [[Isaac Newton|Sir Isaac Newton]], his home, [[Woolsthorpe Manor]], being a visitor attraction. Woolsthorpe-by-Colsterworth village hall was built as a result of an appeal in Newton's memory, and is named after him. Newton was christened at the parish church of St John the Baptist, where a copy of the entry in the register is to be found.<ref name=Church/>\n\n==Heritage==\nThe name Colsterworth is from the [[Old English]] 'colestre' + 'worth' for \"enclosure of the [[Charcoal maker|charcoal burners]]\"; the name appears as \"Colsteuorde\" in the ''[[Domesday Book]]''.\n\nThe village dates from the [[Roman era]]. It is close to [[Ermine Street]], the old Roman road that ran from London directly north to [[Lincoln, Lincolnshire|Lincoln]] and to the Roman road known as [[High Dyke]]. A Roman smelting furnace was found at Colsterworth in 1931, as was a small defended [[Iron Age|Late Iron Age]] settlement in the 1940s.<ref name=CDPC>[http://parishes.lincolnshire.gov.uk/ColsterworthandDistrict/section.asp?docId=68032 \"Colsterworth and District Parish Council\"], Lincolnshire.gov.uk. Retrieved 30 April 2012.</ref>\n\nColsterworth is raised upon a slight [[limestone]] ridge, with the [[River Witham]] running below on the western side and dividing the two villages. The old hamlet of [[Twyford, Lincolnshire|Twyford]] has been incorporated by the growth of Colsterworth, but the name survives in the names of some houses and in [[Twyford Wood]]. The area between Colsterworth Church and Twyford was once known as Dunkirk. Colsterworth, Woolsthorpe and Twyford are all separately entered in the ''Domesday Book'' of 1086.<ref name=VAGwelcome>[http://www.villagearchivegroup.com/ \"Welcome to the Village Archive Group web site!\"], Villagearchivegroup.com. Retrieved 30 April 2012</ref> The village belonged to the historical [[hundred (county subdivision)|wapentake]] of [[Winnibriggs and Threo]].<ref>[https://archive.is/20121205081358/http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/relationships.jsp?u_id=10005838&c_id=%20 \"Winnibriggs and Threo Wap\"], [[A Vision of Britain through Time]], Retrieved 16 March 2012.</ref>\n\nThe [[Inclosure Acts|enclosure]]s of the land in 1808 allowed the local landlords to increase their holdings. Thirty villagers also received land, but some sold on to avoid the compulsory expense of fencing it. In Colsterworth the rector commuted his [[tithe|tythes]] for 398 acres, in addition to his 11 acres of [[glebe]]. The position of Colsterworth on the Great York Road, later the [[Great North Road (Great Britain)|Great North Road]], became important as soon as the [[turnpike trust|turnpike road]] was completed in 1752. It was appointed a post town, and by the mid-19th century had a thriving coaching trade. There were numerous inns \u2013 ten at one time. However, the village was bypassed in 1935.<ref>[http://parishes.lincolnshire.gov.uk/Files/Parish/418/VillagesThree12.pdf \"Villages Three - A short history of the Parish of St John the Baptist, Colsterworth\"], Lincolnshire.gov.uk. Retrieved 30 April 2012</ref>\n\nThe old coaching inns have been transformed into houses or business properties, such as The George House and The Sun Pottery, or demolished completely. The ''White Lion'' [[public house]], standing opposite the parish church of [[St John the Baptist]], alone now serves the population. About that time, ironstone workings began. These were closed in the 1970s and the site rehabilitated.<ref name=VAG>[http://www.villagearchivegroup.com/index.php?page=history-of-colsterworth \"History of Colsterworth\"], Villagearchivegroup.com. Retrieved 30 April 2012</ref>\n\nColsterworth lies one mile to the west of Twyford Wood, which was the site of a Second World War airfield [[RAF North Witham]], and still retains military artefacts, including open runways and a derelict control tower. After the war, the grassed part of the airfield was planted with oaks and conifers. This grassland habitat is home to a regionally important colony of [[Dingy Skipper|dingy]] and [[Grizzled Skipper|grizzled]] [[Skipper (butterfly)|skipper butterflies]].<ref>[http://www.forestry.gov.uk/website/wildwoods.nsf/LUWebDocsByKey/EnglandLincolnshireKestevenForestTwyfordWood \"Explore Twyford Wood\"], Forestry.gov.uk. Retrieved 30 April 2012</ref>\n\nIn 1884 the Rev. J. Mirehouse, Rector of Colsterworth, was responsible for the [[Home Office Baby]] publicity stunt.<ref>A. W. Brian Simpson: ''Cannibalism and the Common Law'' (London: The Hambledon Press, 1994), p. 245. [https://books.google.com/books?id=vIZ7bFBjV0YC&pg=PA245&lpg=PA245&dq=Home+Office+Baby+Colsterworth&source=bl&ots=bNLtCuGRvH&sig=Q81npNd2sSzQOjgy69WUTVjvO5g&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjEk7zm_93KAhWhg3IKHUKtCNoQ6AEILDAD#v=onepage&q=Home%20Office%20Baby%20Colsterworth&f=false Retrieved 4 February 2016.]</ref>\n\nThe former [[Lincoln City F.C.|Lincoln City]] footballer [[Ayden Duffy]] was brought up in Colsterworth.<ref>''Grantham Journal'' [http://www.granthamjournal.co.uk/sport/former-colt-ayden-signs-another-year-with-the-imps-1-19203 Retrieved 4 February 2016.]{{Dead link|date=November 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Religion==\n[[File:Colsterworth Church, Lincolnshire by W. Stukeley (1722).png|thumb|280px|A drawing of St John the Baptist's church,<br />by the antiquarian [[William Stukeley]], 1722]]\n[[File:Newton sundial 2.jpg|thumb|280px|Memorial plaque with [[sundial]] plate, cut with a penknife by [[Isaac Newton|Sir Isaac Newton]] in 1651, in St John the Baptist's church]] \nThe parish church of St John the Baptist has been a Grade I [[listed building]] since 1966.<ref>[http://www.britishlistedbuildings.co.uk/en-193254-church-of-st-john-the-baptist-colsterwor#.V7BKY5grLy0]</ref> Its origins go back to [[Anglo-Saxons|Saxon]] times, as indicated by the [[Opus spicatum|herring-bone]] stonework in the [[Apse|chancel]]. The [[Norman architecture|Norman]] arches were preserved during [[Victorian era|Victorian]] renovation, of which this church is a prime example. The surrounding churchyard has been closed for almost a century but is kept in order by the [[Parish councils in England|Parish Council]]. Inside the church, behind the organ, is a stone [[sundial]] plate that was cut with a penknife by [[Isaac Newton|Sir Isaac Newton]] when nine years of age. The stone, which has no [[gnomon]], is mounted upside down below a carved wooden [[effigy]] of the scientist.<ref name=CDPC/> Newton's mother, Hannah Ayscough (died 1679) and father, also called Isaac (died 1642), were buried in the church.<ref name=Church>[http://parishes.lincolnshire.gov.uk/Files/Parish/418/StJohnChurchhistoryGuide_A5.pdf \"The Church of Saint John the Baptist,Colsterworth\"]. Retrieved 30 April 2012</ref>\n\nSt John the Baptist's belongs to the Colsterworth Group of [[Anglicanism|Anglican]] churches, sharing a priest with Holy Cross at [[Great Ponton]], [[Guthlac of Crowland|St Guthlac's]] at [[Little Ponton|Little Ponton with Woodnook]], [[James, son of Zebedee|St James's]] at [[Skillington]] and [[St Andrew and St Mary's Church, Stoke Rochford|St Andrew and St Mary's]] at [[Stoke Rochford]] with [[Easton, Lincolnshire|Easton]]. It is in the deanery of [[Beltisloe]] and the [[Diocese of Lincoln]].\n\n[[Methodism]] came to Colsterworth about 1795. The present Methodist church in Back Lane dates back to the 1830s<ref name=VAG/> and is part of the Grantham and Vale of Belvoir Methodist Circuit.<ref>Circuit website [http://www.gvbcircuit.org.uk/colsterworth.html Retrieved 4 February 2016.]</ref>\n\n==Economy and amenities==\nThere is little employment in the village itself. During and for some time after the Second World War, work was available at the ironstone excavations,<ref>[http://www.irsociety.co.uk/Archives/3+4/Ore2.gif \"Colsterworth\"], Industrial Railway Society.</ref> but after operations ceased the site was filled and levelled. A tyre depot and [[Christian Salvesen]] food cold-store offer local jobs. Farming, the traditional occupation that previously absorbed most of the workforce, still provides some employment, for instance at the [[Openfield]] grain cooperative on the former RAF station. There is work at fast-food restaurants [[Little Chef]], [[OK Diner]] and [[Travelodge]] on the A1, and at the nearby [[Stoke Rochford Hall]], a conference and function centre.<ref>Promotional site [http://www.stokerochfordhall.co.uk/?gclid=CM2tirSD3soCFQT4wgodYUoEfg Retrieved 4 February 2016.]</ref>\n\nThe village has a post office, a medical surgery, a [[The Co-operative Group|Co-op]] store and a hairdresser, with greengrocer, butcher and fishmonger mobile shops. There is a mobile library service.<ref>[http://parishes.lincolnshire.gov.uk/Files/Parish/418/DistrictMobileDSKTuesdaysRoute2.pdf \"Welcome to the Mobile Library Service\"], Lincolnshire.gov.uk. Retrieved 30 April 2012.</ref>\n\nOther facilities in the village include a sports and social club, a village hall, a youth centre that doubles as a nursery, and three playgrounds. There is another village hall at North Witham.<ref>Photographs and captions: Lincolnshire County site [http://parishes.lincolnshire.gov.uk/ColsterworthandDistrict/section.asp?catId=20760 Retrieved 4 February 2016.]</ref>\n\nColsterworth's Church of England [[primary school]] also provides for children in neighbouring villages. It has about 100 pupils in five classes that span the seven years of primary education.<ref>[https://archive.is/20120731031649/http://www.colsterworth.lincs.sch.uk/page_viewer.asp?page=About+The+School&pid=31 \"About The School\"], Colsterworth.lincs.sch.uk. Retrieved 30 April 2012.</ref> The school is a \"guardian school\" for nearby [[Woolsthorpe Manor]],<ref>[http://www.colsterworth.lincs.sch.uk/page_viewer.asp?page=Our+Community&pid=8 \"Our Community\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120312214004/http://www.colsterworth.lincs.sch.uk/page_viewer.asp?page=Our+Community&pid=8 |date=12 March 2012 }}, Colsterworth.lincs.sch.uk. Retrieved 30 April 2012</ref> the birthplace of Sir [[Isaac Newton]].<ref>[http://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/woolsthorpe-manor/join-in/ \"Woolsthorpe Manor - Join in\"], Nationaltrust.org.uk. Retrieved 30 April 2012</ref> The new school buildings that opened in Back Lane in 1973 replaced earlier ones in School Lane, dating from 1824 and 1895.<ref name=VAG/>\n\nThe A1 trunk road at Colsterworth was redeveloped in 2010, when Colsterworth roundabout was removed and a road bridge over the A1 added for local traffic, to address safety and traffic congestion concerns.<ref>[http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20120810121037/http://www.highways.gov.uk/roads/documents/6_colsterworth_draft_orders.pdf \"A1 Peterborough to Blyth Junction Improvements\"], Highways Agency. Retrieved 18 July 2011.</ref> The village is on the bus route between Grantham and Witham.<ref>[http://parishes.lincolnshire.gov.uk/Files/Parish/418/Bus_Timetable__A4.pdf \"Grantham - South Witham\"], Lincolnshire.gov.uk. Retrieved 30 April 2012.</ref>\n\n==Dwellings and archive group==\nAlthough the oldest dwellings are of [[limestone]], brick houses of the 1920s and 1930s are interposed amongst them. During the 1970s a large estate, Woodlands Drive, was built on ground previously belonging to Colsterworth House,<ref>[http://parishes.lincolnshire.gov.uk/ColsterworthandDistrict/imageDetail.asp?id=66363 \"Colsterworth House\"], Lincolnshire.gov.uk. Retrieved 30 April 2012</ref> which was demolished. The land between the village and the A1 was developed into a new housing estate. More recently, in 2009, a further housing development commenced on land previously utilised for steel storage and distribution, known as Newton Grange.<ref>Promotional news report [http://www.easier.com/60848-new-phase-of-homes-opens-at-newton-grange.html Retrieved 4 February 2016.]</ref>\n\nA village archive group was founded to record memories of Colsterworth people for posterity. The group's aim is to chronicle local social history and changes in dialect, and publish material as a resource and educational tool in book and DVD form. It has been funded by Lincolnshire Community Champions and the Local Heritage Initiative, now under the auspices of the [[National Lottery (United Kingdom)|Heritage Lottery Funding]].<ref name=VAGwelcome/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commons category-inline|Colsterworth}}\n*[https://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/woolsthorpe-manor \"Woolsthorpe Manor\"], [[National Trust for Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty|National Trust]]\n*[http://www.britishpathe.com/record.php?id=38199 \"Isaac Newton\"], Newsreel, British Pathe\n*[http://parishes.lincolnshire.gov.uk/ColsterworthandDistrict/ Colsterworth and District Parish Council]\n\n{{Portal bar|England|United Kingdom}}\n{{Lincolnshire|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Lincolnshire]]\n[[Category:Civil parishes in Lincolnshire]]\n[[Category:South Kesteven District]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2014}}\n{{Infobox UK place \n|country = England\n|coordinates = {{coord|52.80554|-0.61825|display=inline,title}}\n|official_name = Colsterworth\n|static_image_name = St John the Baptist, Colsterworth 8.jpg\n|static_image_caption = Parish church of St John the Baptist\n|population = 1,713\n|civil_parish = Colsterworth\n|shire_district = [[South Kesteven]]\n|shire_county = [[Lincolnshire]]\n|region = East Midlands\n|constituency_westminster = \n|post_town = GRANTHAM\n|postcode_district = NG33\n|postcode_area = NG\n|dial_code = \n|os_grid_reference = SK932240\n|london_distance_mi= 90<!-- straight line per MOS \u2013 constant and comparable with other place distances -->\n|london_direction= S\n}}\n'''Colsterworth''' is a village and [[civil parish]] in the [[South Kesteven]] district of [[Lincolnshire]], England. It lies less than half a mile (0.8&nbsp;km) west of the [[A1 road (Great Britain)|A1]], about {{convert|7|mi|km|0}} south of [[Grantham]], and {{convert|12|mi|km|0}} north-west of [[Stamford, Lincolnshire|Stamford]]. The village, with the hamlet of [[Woolsthorpe-by-Colsterworth]], had a population of 1,713 at the time of the 2011 Census in an area of {{convert|1465|ha}}.<ref>Office of National Statistics [http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=7&b=11122217&c=Colsterworth&d=16&e=61&g=6447427&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&p=1&r=1&s=1454584397276&enc=1&dsFamilyId=2491 Retrieved 4 February 2016.]</ref>\n\n==Civil parish==\nThe civil parish includes the village of Woolsthorpe-by-Colsterworth, {{convert|0.6|mi|0}} north-west of Colsterworth. The parish shares a [[grouped parish council]] with [[Gunby and Stainby]] and [[North Witham]], known as Colsterworth and District Parish Council.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Colsterworth and District Parishes |url=http://parishes.lincolnshire.gov.uk/ColsterworthandDistrict/|work=Lincolnshire Parish Councils; South Kesteven |publisher=Lincolnshire county council |accessdate=8 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Woolsthorpe-by-Colsterworth===\n{{main|Woolsthorpe-by-Colsterworth}}\nWoolsthorpe-by-Colsterworth is notable as the birthplace of [[Isaac Newton|Sir Isaac Newton]], his home, [[Woolsthorpe Manor]], being a visitor attraction. Woolsthorpe-by-Colsterworth village hall was built as a result of an appeal in Newton's memory, and is named after him. Newton was christened at the parish church of St John the Baptist, where a copy of the entry in the register is to be found.<ref name=Church/>\n\n==Heritage==\nThe name Colsterworth is from the [[Old English]] 'colestre' + 'worth' for \"enclosure of the [[Charcoal maker|charcoal burners]]\"; the name appears as \"Colsteuorde\" in the ''[[Domesday Book]]''.\n\nThe village dates from the [[Roman era]]. It is close to [[Ermine Street]], the old Roman road that ran from London directly north to [[Lincoln, Lincolnshire|Lincoln]] and to the Roman road known as [[High Dyke]]. A Roman smelting furnace was found at Colsterworth in 1931, as was a small defended [[Iron Age|Late Iron Age]] settlement in the 1940s.<ref name=CDPC>[http://parishes.lincolnshire.gov.uk/ColsterworthandDistrict/section.asp?docId=68032 \"Colsterworth and District Parish Council\"], Lincolnshire.gov.uk. Retrieved 30 April 2012.</ref>\n\nColsterworth is raised upon a slight [[limestone]] ridge, with the [[River Witham]] running below on the western side and dividing the two villages. The old hamlet of [[Twyford, Lincolnshire|Twyford]] has been incorporated by the growth of Colsterworth, but the name survives in the names of some houses and in [[Twyford Wood]]. The area between Colsterworth Church and Twyford was once known as Dunkirk. Colsterworth, Woolsthorpe and Twyford are all separately entered in the ''Domesday Book'' of 1086.<ref name=VAGwelcome>[http://www.villagearchivegroup.com/ \"Welcome to the Village Archive Group web site!\"], Villagearchivegroup.com. Retrieved 30 April 2012</ref> The village belonged to the historical [[hundred (county subdivision)|wapentake]] of [[Winnibriggs and Threo]].<ref>[https://archive.is/20121205081358/http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/relationships.jsp?u_id=10005838&c_id=%20 \"Winnibriggs and Threo Wap\"], [[A Vision of Britain through Time]], Retrieved 16 March 2012.</ref>\n\nThe [[Inclosure Acts|enclosure]]s of the land in 1808 allowed the local landlords to increase their holdings. Thirty villagers also received land, but some sold on to avoid the compulsory expense of fencing it. In Colsterworth the rector commuted his [[tithe|tythes]] for 398 acres, in addition to his 11 acres of [[glebe]]. The position of Colsterworth on the Great York Road, later the [[Great North Road (Great Britain)|Great North Road]], became important as soon as the [[turnpike trust|turnpike road]] was completed in 1752. It was appointed a post town, and by the mid-19th century had a thriving coaching trade. There were numerous inns \u2013 ten at one time. However, the village was bypassed in 1935.<ref>[http://parishes.lincolnshire.gov.uk/Files/Parish/418/VillagesThree12.pdf \"Villages Three - A short history of the Parish of St John the Baptist, Colsterworth\"], Lincolnshire.gov.uk. Retrieved 30 April 2012</ref>\n\nThe old coaching inns have been transformed into houses or business properties, such as The George House and The Sun Pottery, or demolished completely. The ''White Lion'' [[public house]], standing opposite the parish church of [[St John the Baptist]], alone now serves the population. About that time, ironstone workings began. These were closed in the 1970s and the site rehabilitated.<ref name=VAG>[http://www.villagearchivegroup.com/index.php?page=history-of-colsterworth \"History of Colsterworth\"], Villagearchivegroup.com. Retrieved 30 April 2012</ref>\n\nColsterworth lies one mile to the west of Twyford Wood, which was the site of a Second World War airfield [[RAF North Witham]], and still retains military artefacts, including open runways and a derelict control tower. After the war, the grassed part of the airfield was planted with oaks and conifers. This grassland habitat is home to a regionally important colony of [[Dingy Skipper|dingy]] and [[Grizzled Skipper|grizzled]] [[Skipper (butterfly)|skipper butterflies]].<ref>[http://www.forestry.gov.uk/website/wildwoods.nsf/LUWebDocsByKey/EnglandLincolnshireKestevenForestTwyfordWood \"Explore Twyford Wood\"], Forestry.gov.uk. Retrieved 30 April 2012</ref>\n\nIn 1884 the Rev. J. Mirehouse, Rector of Colsterworth, was responsible for the [[Home Office Baby]] publicity stunt.<ref>A. W. Brian Simpson: ''Cannibalism and the Common Law'' (London: The Hambledon Press, 1994), p. 245. [https://books.google.com/books?id=vIZ7bFBjV0YC&pg=PA245&lpg=PA245&dq=Home+Office+Baby+Colsterworth&source=bl&ots=bNLtCuGRvH&sig=Q81npNd2sSzQOjgy69WUTVjvO5g&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjEk7zm_93KAhWhg3IKHUKtCNoQ6AEILDAD#v=onepage&q=Home%20Office%20Baby%20Colsterworth&f=false Retrieved 4 February 2016.]</ref>\n\nThe former [[Lincoln City F.C.|Lincoln City]] footballer [[Ayden Duffy]] was brought up in Colsterworth.<ref>''Grantham Journal'' [http://www.granthamjournal.co.uk/sport/former-colt-ayden-signs-another-year-with-the-imps-1-19203 Retrieved 4 February 2016.]{{Dead link|date=November 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Religion==\n[[File:Colsterworth Church, Lincolnshire by W. Stukeley (1722).png|thumb|280px|A drawing of St John the Baptist's church,<br />by the antiquarian [[William Stukeley]], 1722]]\n[[File:Newton sundial 2.jpg|thumb|280px|Memorial plaque with [[sundial]] plate, cut with a penknife by [[Isaac Newton|Sir Isaac Newton]] in 1651, in St John the Baptist's church]] \nThe parish church of St John the Baptist has been a Grade I [[listed building]] since 1966.<ref>[http://www.britishlistedbuildings.co.uk/en-193254-church-of-st-john-the-baptist-colsterwor#.V7BKY5grLy0]</ref> Its origins go back to [[Anglo-Saxons|Saxon]] times, as indicated by the [[Opus spicatum|herring-bone]] stonework in the [[Apse|chancel]]. The [[Norman architecture|Norman]] arches were preserved during [[Victorian era|Victorian]] renovation, of which this church is a prime example. The surrounding churchyard has been closed for almost a century but is kept in order by the [[Parish councils in England|Parish Council]]. Inside the church, behind the organ, is a stone [[sundial]] plate that was cut with a penknife by [[Isaac Newton|Sir Isaac Newton]] when nine years of age. The stone, which has no [[gnomon]], is mounted upside down below a carved wooden [[effigy]] of the scientist.<ref name=CDPC/> Newton's mother, Hannah Ayscough (died 1679) and father, also called Isaac (died 1642), were buried in the church.<ref name=Church>[http://parishes.lincolnshire.gov.uk/Files/Parish/418/StJohnChurchhistoryGuide_A5.pdf \"The Church of Saint John the Baptist,Colsterworth\"]. Retrieved 30 April 2012</ref>\n\nSt John the Baptist's belongs to the Colsterworth Group of [[Anglicanism|Anglican]] churches, sharing a priest with Holy Cross at [[Great Ponton]], [[Guthlac of Crowland|St Guthlac's]] at [[Little Ponton|Little Ponton with Woodnook]], [[James, son of Zebedee|St James's]] at [[Skillington]] and [[St Andrew and St Mary's Church, Stoke Rochford|St Andrew and St Mary's]] at [[Stoke Rochford]] with [[Easton, Lincolnshire|Easton]]. It is in the deanery of [[Beltisloe]] and the [[Diocese of Lincoln]].\n\n[[Methodism]] came to Colsterworth about 1795. The present Methodist church in Back Lane dates back to the 1830s<ref name=VAG/> and is part of the Grantham and Vale of Belvoir Methodist Circuit.<ref>Circuit website [http://www.gvbcircuit.org.uk/colsterworth.html Retrieved 4 February 2016.]</ref>\n\n==Economy and amenities==\nThere is little employment in the village itself. During and for some time after the Second World War, work was available at the ironstone excavations,<ref>[http://www.irsociety.co.uk/Archives/3+4/Ore2.gif \"Colsterworth\"], Industrial Railway Society.</ref> but after operations ceased the site was filled and levelled. A tyre depot and [[Christian Salvesen]] food cold-store offer local jobs. Farming, the traditional occupation that previously absorbed most of the workforce, still provides some employment, for instance at the [[Openfield]] grain cooperative on the former RAF station. There is work at fast-food restaurants [[Little Chef]], [[OK Diner]] and [[Travelodge]] on the A1, and at the nearby [[Stoke Rochford Hall]], a conference and function centre.<ref>Promotional site [http://www.stokerochfordhall.co.uk/?gclid=CM2tirSD3soCFQT4wgodYUoEfg Retrieved 4 February 2016.]</ref>\n\nThe village has a post office, a medical surgery, a [[The Co-operative Group|Co-op]] store and a hairdresser, with greengrocer, butcher and fishmonger mobile shops. There is a mobile library service.<ref>[http://parishes.lincolnshire.gov.uk/Files/Parish/418/DistrictMobileDSKTuesdaysRoute2.pdf \"Welcome to the Mobile Library Service\"], Lincolnshire.gov.uk. Retrieved 30 April 2012.</ref>\n\nOther facilities in the village include a sports and social club, a village hall, a youth centre that doubles as a nursery, and three playgrounds. There is another village hall at North Witham.<ref>Photographs and captions: Lincolnshire County site [http://parishes.lincolnshire.gov.uk/ColsterworthandDistrict/section.asp?catId=20760 Retrieved 4 February 2016.]</ref>\n\nColsterworth's Church of England [[primary school]] also provides for children in neighbouring villages. It has about 100 pupils in five classes that span the seven years of primary education.<ref>[https://archive.is/20120731031649/http://www.colsterworth.lincs.sch.uk/page_viewer.asp?page=About+The+School&pid=31 \"About The School\"], Colsterworth.lincs.sch.uk. Retrieved 30 April 2012.</ref> The school is a \"guardian school\" for nearby [[Woolsthorpe Manor]],<ref>[http://www.colsterworth.lincs.sch.uk/page_viewer.asp?page=Our+Community&pid=8 \"Our Community\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120312214004/http://www.colsterworth.lincs.sch.uk/page_viewer.asp?page=Our+Community&pid=8 |date=12 March 2012 }}, Colsterworth.lincs.sch.uk. Retrieved 30 April 2012</ref> the birthplace of Sir [[Isaac Newton]].<ref>[http://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/woolsthorpe-manor/join-in/ \"Woolsthorpe Manor - Join in\"], Nationaltrust.org.uk. Retrieved 30 April 2012</ref> The new school buildings that opened in Back Lane in 1973 replaced earlier ones in School Lane, dating from 1824 and 1895.<ref name=VAG/>\n\nThe A1 trunk road at Colsterworth was redeveloped in 2010, when Colsterworth roundabout was removed and a road bridge over the A1 added for local traffic, to address safety and traffic congestion concerns.<ref>[http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20120810121037/http://www.highways.gov.uk/roads/documents/6_colsterworth_draft_orders.pdf \"A1 Peterborough to Blyth Junction Improvements\"], Highways Agency. Retrieved 18 July 2011.</ref> The village is on the bus route between Grantham and Witham.<ref>[http://parishes.lincolnshire.gov.uk/Files/Parish/418/Bus_Timetable__A4.pdf \"Grantham - South Witham\"], Lincolnshire.gov.uk. Retrieved 30 April 2012.</ref>\n\n==Dwellings and archive group==\nAlthough the oldest dwellings are of [[limestone]], brick houses of the 1920s and 1930s are interposed amongst them. During the 1970s a large estate, Woodlands Drive, was built on ground previously belonging to Colsterworth House,<ref>[http://parishes.lincolnshire.gov.uk/ColsterworthandDistrict/imageDetail.asp?id=66363 \"Colsterworth House\"], Lincolnshire.gov.uk. Retrieved 30 April 2012</ref> which was demolished. The land between the village and the A1 was developed into a new housing estate. More recently, in 2009, a further housing development commenced on land previously utilised for steel storage and distribution, known as Newton Grange.<ref>Promotional news report [http://www.easier.com/60848-new-phase-of-homes-opens-at-newton-grange.html Retrieved 4 February 2016.]</ref>\n\nA village archive group was founded to record memories of Colsterworth people for posterity. The group's aim is to chronicle local social history and changes in dialect, and publish material as a resource and educational tool in book and DVD form. It has been funded by Lincolnshire Community Champions and the Local Heritage Initiative, now under the auspices of the [[National Lottery (United Kingdom)|Heritage Lottery Funding]].<ref name=VAGwelcome/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commons category-inline|Colsterworth}}\n*[https://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/woolsthorpe-manor \"Woolsthorpe Manor\"], [[National Trust for Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty|National Trust]]\n*[http://www.britishpathe.com/record.php?id=38199 \"Isaac Newton\"], Newsreel, British Pathe\n*[http://parishes.lincolnshire.gov.uk/ColsterworthandDistrict/ Colsterworth and District Parish Council]\n\n{{Portal bar|England|United Kingdom}}\n{{Lincolnshire|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Lincolnshire]]\n[[Category:Civil parishes in Lincolnshire]]\n[[Category:South Kesteven District]]\n", "name_user": "KJD 0115gbr", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Colsterworth"}
